  <a href="#1" id="1">
   For almost a decade, Margaret Thatcher was regarded at the White House as America's best friend, the trusted ally whose strong views reinforced the conservative tone of administration policies.
  </a>
  <a href="#2" id="2">
   Among Western allies, she was alone at Ronald Reagan's side in 1986 in supporting the U.S. bombing of Libya.
  </a>
  <a href="#3" id="3">
   In the Persian Gulf crisis, she boldly joined with George Bush in sending troops to the Middle East.
  </a>
  <a href="#4" id="4">
   Together they advocated a hard line toward Moscow and championed military readiness - even though she was the first to recognize Mikhail S. Gorbachev as a leader she could do business with.
  </a>
  <a href="#5" id="5">
   Bush and Mrs. Thatcher disagreed publicly last year over her government's decision to deport Vietnamese and Cambodian ``boat people'' who were fleeing their countries to Hong Kong.
  </a>
